  "final_answer": "## Two Specific Pre-Merger Revenue/Cost Flows Eliminated in Consolidation\n\nBased on the SpaceX S-1 filed May 20, 2026, the filing identifies two categories of eliminated flows under common-control recast accounting. All historical financial statements have been retrospectively recast to combine SpaceX, xAI (merged February 2, 2026), and X Holdings (merged into xAI March 28, 2025) for all periods presented, with \"all historical related party transactions between the entities...eliminated in consolidation.\"\n\n---\n\n### Elimination #1: Space Segment → Connectivity Segment — Internal Starlink Launch Services\n\n**Filing Disclosure (Explicit):** The S-1 explicitly states: *\"For launches of our Starlink satellites, the Company does not recognize any inter-segment revenue, rather those launch costs are capitalized in satellites in Property, plant, and equipment, net.\"*\n\n**Nature of the Flow:** The Space segment (seller) provides launch services to deploy Starlink satellites for the Connectivity segment (buyer). In 2025, of 2,213 total metric tons of mass to orbit, **1,901 metric tons (85.9%) were internal payloads** (Starlink constellation deployments), while only 312 metric tons were external customer payloads. The Space segment completed 170 launches in 2025, the vast majority dedicated to internal Starlink deployments.\n\n**Accounting Treatment:** Rather than recording inter-segment revenue in the Space segment and a corresponding expense in the Connectivity segment, the launch costs (flight vehicle costs, parts, labor, and allocated overhead) are transferred and **capitalized directly into the Connectivity segment's PP&E** as \"satellites\" and subsequently depreciated over their useful lives within Connectivity segment cost of revenue.\n\n**Impact on Seller-Segment Economics — DEFLATES:** This elimination **materially deflates** the Space segment's reported revenue and apparent economic scale. The Space segment reported only **$4,086 million in revenue** for 2025, reflecting exclusively external customer launches and government contracts. The segment's true operational throughput—evidenced by 1,901 metric tons of internal mass to orbit—is entirely absent from its top line. The Space segment reported a loss from operations of $(657) million and Adjusted EBITDA of only $653 million in 2025, figures that do not capture the foundational strategic value the segment provides as the internal launch provider for the company's most profitable segment (Connectivity generated $7,168 million in Adjusted EBITDA in 2025). Management acknowledges this distortion by supplementing financial metrics with operational KPIs like \"Mass to Orbit\" to demonstrate the segment's true scale.\n\n---\n\n### Elimination #2: xAI ↔ X Holdings — Pre-Merger Intercompany Technology and Data Flows\n\n**Filing Disclosure (Blanket Elimination with Operational Context):** The S-1 states: *\"All historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation.\"* While the filing does not itemize the specific dollar amounts of pre-merger intercompany billing between xAI and X Holdings, it extensively describes the deep operational integration that necessarily generated intercompany revenue and cost flows before the March 28, 2025 merger:\n\n- **xAI → X Holdings (Grok AI technology/services):** xAI developed and provided the Grok large language model, which is deeply integrated into the X platform with \"front and center real estate.\" As of March 31, 2026, 117 million MAUs on X actively used Grok's AI features. Before the merger, xAI (as a separate legal entity) would have charged X Holdings for Grok AI technology licensing, compute services, or API access to power these features on the X platform.\n\n- **X Holdings → xAI (Data access and distribution):** X serves as a *\"foundational distribution and data engine\"* for xAI's AI ecosystem, providing Grok with *\"direct, real-time access to the information and human discourse on X\"* (approximately 350 million daily posts). Before the merger, X Holdings (as a separate legal entity) would have charged xAI for data licensing, platform distribution access, or user reach that grounds Grok's training and inference capabilities.\n\n**Accounting Treatment:** Because xAI and X Holdings were separate legal entities under common control (Elon Musk's majority voting interest) before the March 28, 2025 merger, any pre-merger financial exchanges between them—whether xAI invoicing X for Grok technology services or X invoicing xAI for data access and distribution—were classified as related-party transactions and **entirely eliminated** in the retrospective recast. The combined entity now reports a single \"AI segment\" with $3,201 million in 2025 revenue, disaggregated only into \"Advertising\" ($1,844M) and \"AI Solutions & Infrastructure\" ($1,357M), with no breakdown of former intercompany flows.\n\n**Impact on Seller-Segment Economics — DEFLATES (for each entity as standalone seller):** The elimination **deflates** the reported standalone economics of whichever entity was the seller in each flow. If xAI charged X Holdings for Grok AI technology/services, that revenue is eliminated from xAI's historical standalone top line. If X Holdings charged xAI for data access/distribution, that revenue is eliminated from X Holdings' historical standalone top line. However, because both entities are now combined into the single AI segment in the recast consolidated financials, the net effect on the **AI segment's reported economics is neutral**—the elimination removes both the intercompany revenue and the corresponding intercompany expense, leaving only external third-party revenue (advertising, subscriptions, data licensing, API access) visible. The absence of itemized disclosure means analysts cannot assess the pre-merger standalone profitability of xAI versus X Holdings separately.\n\n---\n\n### Important Disclosure Limitation\n\nThe filing's blanket elimination statement—*\"all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation\"*—does not provide a schedule or itemization of the specific intercompany revenue or cost flows between SpaceX, xAI, and X Holdings. The specific dollar amounts, transfer pricing methodologies, and contractual terms of pre-merger intercompany agreements are **not disclosed** in the S-1. The two eliminations identified above are derived from: (1) the explicit inter-segment launch services accounting policy disclosure, and (2) the filing's detailed description of the xAI-X operational integration combined with the blanket elimination statement. Any additional pre-merger flows (e.g., SpaceX providing Starlink connectivity to xAI facilities, or shared administrative services) are encompassed by the blanket elimination but are not specifically described in the filing.\n\n{\n  \"sources\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\",\n      \"name\": \"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (Filed May 20, 2026)\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
